Jason writes...
>...I want a game system that can
>handle any version or set of attributes a GM would like to use.  The system
>would suggest a set or sets to use, but can accomodate the addition or
>subtraction of attributes.  THIS IS WHAT A UNIVERSAL GAME SYSTEM *COULD*
>ACCOMPLISH.  (might be too hard for this group to do though).

I'm of the opinion that we've got to draw the line somewhere.  I've previously
been of the opinion that we've been getting too specific; "Basis" is sticky to
pin down.  I think I saw six versions of good ole DEX rolling around at one
point.  I agreed that some specifying was needed (e.g., Manual Dex vs.
Agility), but that a limit had to be (albeit arbitrarily) set somewhere.
        This could develop into the opposite problem.  If we set absolutely no
attributes as sacrosanct, what are we actually *doing* at all?  We need to say
something to be useful.  I agree all GMs should take as much flexibility as
they need, but do we really need to give them something so amorphous as this to
begin?

>If we come up with a set of attributes (like above - and I've been guilty of
>it too) and then begin to hang rules etc. off those names etc. we have
>only locked our game up a bit (IMHO).  Changing rules or aspects becomes
>that much more harder, and we have failed (at least partially) in creating
>modularity.

I disagree.  In addition to my comment above, we need some kind of structure to
be of any use at all.  Structure is, by definition, the elimination of certain
undesired forms of flexibility.  I don't think we can have it completely both
ways.

>GENRE:
>
>I agree with Ursus, that it isn't necessary to specify a genre.

Actually, I've been somewhat converted on this point, and discussed the reasons
why in a previous post.  In short: for our ease of design, It might be useful
to design one of the genre-modules first, to work out any bugs we might come
across as they appear.  So long, I say, as we can still extract the FRP module
when done.

>...Adam said it best: "any well-designed game should be very
>adaptable to any genre"

I agree.

